SNP loss is RANDOM by construction. That is the null Section 3 needs.

PRE-REGISTERED:
  P1. chi^2 is far noisier than Section 3 assumes. Under RANDOM 17.7%
      loss, chi^2 falls by >= 51% in more than 10% of replicates.  [~65%]
  P2. If P1 holds, the Section 3 exhibit is within noise and the
      'signature' has no discriminating power.       [conditional on P1]
  P3. chi^2 ~ N holds only for a REJECTED model. For an ACCEPTED model
      chi^2 is basis-invariant. Section 3 states the scaling law
      unconditionally, and it is wrong to.                        [~80%]
  P4. If the fall IS anomalous, Section 3 survives and finally gets
      the null distribution it admits it owes.

