 VERDICT
==========================================================

Under RANDOM 17.7% SNP loss, chi^2 fell by 51% or more in
  0% of 20 replicates.

  SECTION 3 SURVIVES. A 51% fall is rare under random loss. The
  exhibit's chi^2 collapse IS anomalous, and this run is the null
  distribution Section 3.4 admits it owes. Report both.

--- and P3, which Section 3 gets wrong either way ---
 frac      n chisq_rej chisq_ok ratio_rej ratio_ok n_ratio
 0.50 556426      17.5     8.43      1.26     1.62   0.620
 0.75 834539      18.1     8.32      1.30     1.60   0.929

  If ratio_rej tracks n_ratio but ratio_ok does not, then chi^2 ~ N
  holds ONLY for a rejected model. Section 3 states the law
  unconditionally. That is wrong, and it matters: an analyst applying
  the chi^2/N rule to a model that FITS will conclude non-random SNP
  loss from a statistic that was never going to scale.

